[{"id":27939,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"All molecules have same hybridisation i.e <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> and have similar structure, the T-shaped. So,they are isostructural<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fde9f1f7-f029-42ae-af36-bb396037e832-image.png\" style=\"width: 343px; height: 170px;\" /><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27968,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CHCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{Cl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2$","$\\mathrm{CCl}_4$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CCl}_4$ has lowest (zero) dipole moment. This is due to its symmetrical tetrahedral structure. Due to which dipole moment of one bond is cancelled by opposite dipole moment of the other three bonds.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":27918,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A bonding $\\pi$ orbital","A non-bonding orbital","An antibonding $\\sigma$ orbital","An antibonding $\\pi$ orbital"],"answer":3,"solution":"An antibonding $\\pi$ orbital best describes the diagram of a molecular orbital. Two orbitals laterally overlap to form pi bond. Out of phase combination, of these two $p$ orbitals, give $\\pi^*$ MO.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":27873,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["see-saw","planar triangular","T-shaped","trigonal pyramidal"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8966815a-a3a7-4de1-a232-bfb1a97f9e0e-image.png\" style=\"width: 131px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybridised</p><p>T-shaped</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27917,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> - trigonal planar","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> - trigonal planar","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AsF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math> - trigonal bipyramidal","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> - bent"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mi>N</mi><msub><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dfa98479-6f4d-48a0-b8ca-dcca46e3f272-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 128px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> , Trigonal Pyramidal","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27916,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/167a0ad1-26c3-45f4-85b3-94be3f5e9620-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 118px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/63f94b82-bf7c-4481-aed7-86d428750fe5-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 162px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d9a794bd-9583-4841-b669-36822a3313f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 128px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6a31a88-c7a0-4425-adf2-e4c0f4f72602-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 142px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Polar compounds are chemical compounds that are held together by polar covalent bonds. The term &lsquo;polar compound&rsquo; can be defined as a chemical species which consists of two or more atoms that are held together by covalent bonds that are polar in nature due to the unequal sharing of electrons. When two atoms are bound together via a covalent bond&nbsp;the differences in the electronegativities of the bonded atoms may cause the bond pair of electrons to shift closer to the more electronegative atom. This results in the accumulation of a partial positive charge at the location of the more electropositive atom and the accumulation of a partial negative charge at the location of the more electronegative atom. Polar compounds are chemical compounds that are held together by such bonds.</p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7deb58b6-7309-415b-8811-90a43099c16f-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 115px;\" /></p><p>In the bond dipole vector of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math> bond is not subtractive.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27912,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><msubsup><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi> </mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math > <mrow>  <msubsup>   <mi>O</mi>   <mn>2</mn>   <mo>&#x2212;</mo>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>x</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>y</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C0;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>y</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C0;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>1</mn>  </msubsup>  </mrow></math><br><br>Bond Order <math > <mrow>  <mo>=</mo><mfrac>   <mrow>    <mn>6</mn><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow>   <mn>2</mn>  </mfrac>  <mo>=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></mrow></math><br><br><math > <mrow>  <msub>   <mi>O</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>x</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>y</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C0;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>y</mi>   <mn>1</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C0;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>1</mn>  </msubsup>  </mrow></math><br><br>Bond order <math > <mrow>  <mo>=</mo><mfrac>   <mrow>    <mn>6</mn><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow>   <mn>2</mn>  </mfrac>  <mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></math><br><br><math > <mrow>  <msub>   <mi>N</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>x</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  </mrow></math><br><br>Bond order <math > <mrow>  <mo>=</mo><mfrac>   <mrow>    <mn>6</mn><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow>   <mn>2</mn>  </mfrac>  <mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></math><br><br>According to <math><mi>M</mi><mi>O</mi><mi>T</mi></math> ; electronic configuration of <math><msubsup><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></math> is:<br /><br /><math > <mrow>  <msubsup>   <mi>N</mi>   <mn>2</mn>   <mo>+</mo>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>1</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mover>   <mi>&#x03C3;</mi>   <mo>*</mo>  </mover>  <mn>2</mn><msup>   <mi>s</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>x</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>=</mo><mi>&#x03C0;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>y</mi>   <mn>2</mn>  </msubsup>  <mo>&#x003C;</mo><mi>&#x03C3;</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup>   <mi>p</mi>   <mi>z</mi>   <mn>1</mn>  </msubsup>  </mrow></math><br /><br />Bond order <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2.5</mn></math><br /><br />i.e., <math><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></math> bonds and <math><mn>0.5</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi>σ</mi></math> bonds.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27780,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Dipole moment:- The polarity of a covalent bond can be conveniently measured in terms of a physical quantity called dipole moment. The dipole moment is the vector sum of all the bond moments. The molecules with perfect geometries with zero lone pairs have zero dipole moment.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cee0e1ee-f3c6-46ee-962f-cd67edfc80ab.png\" style=\"width: 427px; height: 340px;\"/></p><p>Amongst the given compounds, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>BF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> have zero dipole moments.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27766,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"According to M.O.T.\n$\\mathrm{O}_2 \\rightarrow$ no. of unpaired electrons $=2$\n$\\mathrm{O}_2^{-} \\rightarrow$ no. of unpaired electron $=1$\n$\\mathrm{NO} \\rightarrow$ no. of unpaired electron $=1$\n$\\mathrm{CN}^{-} \\rightarrow$ no. of unpaired electron $=0$\n$\\mathrm{O}_2^{2-} \\rightarrow$ no. of unpaired electron $=0$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27949,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{sp}$ and $\\mathrm{sp}^3$","$\\mathrm{sp}^2$ and $\\mathrm{sp}$","only $\\mathrm{sp}^2$","$\\mathrm{sp}^2$ and $\\mathrm{sp}^3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Hb5zLOJjSehQ_toeAEHVMBCT3bmja8WzycnBExPNKx8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27996,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{XeF}_4$","$\\left[\\mathrm{Ni}(\\mathrm{CN})_4\\right]^{2^{-}}$","$\\mathrm{BF}_4{ }^{-4}$","$\\mathrm{SF}_4$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Total no of valence electrons $=3+7 \\times 4+1=32$\nTotal No of hybrid orbital $=4$\n$\\because$ Hybridisation $=\\mathrm{sp}^3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27846,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow/></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Structures of the given oxides of nitrogen are as follows:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6112accf-3576-4376-b263-02c9220b0669-d629cb99-09be-46f1-98cd-8fe12f4935dc-7.png\" style=\"width: 292px; height: 433px;\" /></p><p>As we can see only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is having an odd electron on the nitrogen atom.It is the correct answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27865,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mn>16</mn></math>&nbsp;electrons)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mo>*</mo><mn>1</mn></msub></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mo>*</mo><mn>1</mn></msub></msubsup><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>&#963;</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></msub></mrow><mo>*</mo></msubsup></math></p><p>Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br />Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br />Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27984,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Be}^{2+}, \\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$","$\\mathrm{Be}^{2+}, \\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$","$\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Be}^{2+}$","$\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Be}^{2+}, \\mathrm{K}^{+}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Higher the charge/size ratio, more is the polarizing power.\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{K}^{+} < \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Be}^{2+}$\nHence, (C) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":27702,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The central atom in $XeO_6^{4-}$ is Xenon (Xe).<br><br>The number of valence electrons in Xe is $8$.<br><br>Let the oxidation state of Xe in $XeO_6^{4-}$ be $x$.<br><br>$x + 6(-2) = -4$<br><br>$x = +8$<br><br>Since the oxidation state of Xe is $+8$, all $8$ of its valence electrons are involved in bonding with the $6$ oxygen atoms. There are no non-bonding electrons left on the central atom.<br><br>Number of lone pairs on Xe $= 0$<br><br>Xe forms $6$ $\\sigma$ bonds with the $6$ oxygen atoms (and $2$ $\\pi$ bonds to satisfy its $+8$ oxidation state and minimize formal charge).<br><br>Number of $\\sigma$ bond-pairs $= 6$<br><br>Total number of $\\sigma$ bond-pairs and lone pairs around the central atom $= 6 + 0 = 6$.<br><br>Answer: $6$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27778,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["(A)-I, (B)-II, (C)-IV, (D)-III","(A) -II, (B)-I, (C)-III, (D)-IV","(A)-III, (B)-IV, (C)-I, (D)-II","(A)-IV, (B)-III, (C)-I, (D)-II"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>(A) The steric number of the central Bromine atom is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math> bond pairs<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math>one lone pair <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>. Hence the shape is square pyramidal structure and the hybridisation is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p><p>(B) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> molecular geometry is bent because it has two bound atoms and two lone pairs on oxygen, the central atom. The two lone pairs on the oxygen atom push the two hydrogen atoms down further away from the oxygen atom and closer to each other, creating a bent shape and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>104</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math> degrees angle between the two <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> atoms.</p><p>(C) The molecular geometry of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is said to be T-shaped. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> acquires such a shape because two lone pairs take up equatorial positions as they require more space and greater repulsions. They are arranged in a trigonal bipyramidal shape with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> bonds and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> lone pairs.</p><p>(D)  <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> has an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> type of hybridisation. In a molecule of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>, each <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math> atom is bonded to four fluorine atoms. </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9a250b9d-65ed-43a7-99a0-d31334723340.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 561px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27994,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Bond length in $\\mathrm{NO}^{+}$is greater than in $\\mathrm{NO}$","Bond length is unpredictable","Bond length in $\\mathrm{NO}^{+}$in equal to that in $\\mathrm{NO}$","Bond length in $\\mathrm{NO}$ is greater than in $\\mathrm{NO}^{+}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Bond order of $\\mathrm{NO}=2.5$\nBond order of $\\mathrm{NO}^{+}=3$\nHigher the bond order shorter is the bond length","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27927,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>33</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>25</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>67</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>33</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<table border=\"1\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Graphite</td>\t\t\t<td>Diamond</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> hybridisation</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> hybridisation</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>67</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math> character<br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos&#952;</mi></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>120</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>66</mn><mo>.67</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math> character<br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>109</mn><mo>'</mo><mn>28</mn></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.33</mo></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27796,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MgO</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>AlN</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is a bent molecule with a central sulfur atom bonded to two oxygen atoms. The oxygen atoms are more electronegative than sulfur, causing a separation of charge. This results in a bent molecular geometry and a net dipole moment, making <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> a polar molecule.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is a trigonal pyramidal molecule with a central nitrogen atom bonded to three hydrogen atoms. Again, the electronegativity difference between nitrogen and hydrogen leads to a separation of charge. The arrangement of the atoms in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> gives it a net dipole moment, making it a polar molecule.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27788,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math> are correct","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are correct","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are correct","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are correct"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, nitrogen is having three bond pairs and a lone pair, hence, it has pyramidal shape.</p><p>The bond order&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;The bond order&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>. Bond length is inversely related to bond order. Hence,&nbsp;bond length of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is shorter than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Isoelectronic species have identical bond order</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71b694b0-2fc5-4116-b7fc-8ba75e4aa7c3.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 113px;\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b0b17e0-a2cd-40ce-a823-a8390889b0fb.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 90px;\" /></p><p>Dipole moment of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> is more than that of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math> due to higher electronegativity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27867,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["(a)-(i), (b)-( ii), (c)-(v) and (d)-(iii)","(a)-(ii), (b)-(i), (c)-(iv) and (d)-(v)","(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(v) and (d)-(iv)","(a)-(iv), (b)-(iii), (c)-(ii) and (d)-(v)"],"answer":2,"solution":"(a) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybridisation<br />(b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>IF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> hybridisation<br />(c)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>-</mo><mi>sp</mi></math> hybridisation<br />(d) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> hybridisation","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27985,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{O}_7^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{B}_2$","$\\mathrm{N}_2^{+}$","$\\mathrm{O}_2$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":27761,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A, B, D only","A, D, E only","A only","A, B, C only"],"answer":1,"solution":"(A) Generally hydrogen bonding exists when $\\mathrm{H}$ is covalently bonded to the highly electronegative atom like $\\mathrm{F}, \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{N}$.\n(B) Intramolecular $\\mathrm{H}$ bonding is present in\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VbHoLIQPukXwW2rGaZplMHhS4cMYmUUbhwAYHgG_ZR8.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(C) Intermolecular Hydrogen bonding is present in $\\mathrm{HF}$\n(D) The magnitude has Hydrogen bonding in solid state is greater than liquid state.\n(E) Hydrogen bonding has powerfull effect on the structure \\& properties of compound like melting point, boiling point, density etc.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27910,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></math>","<math><mi>C</mi></math>","<math><mi>S</mi><mi>i</mi></math>","<math><mi>G</mi><mi>e</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;forms most stable <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p&#960;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>p&#960;</mi></math> bonds because it has high bond dissociation energy, more electronegativity, high ionization energy and vacant <math><mi>d</mi><mo>-</mo></math> orbital is unavailable. While others have vacant orbital and low bond dissociation enthalpy and low ionisation enthalpy","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27842,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The hybridization is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybridization and phosphorous atom forms five <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybrid orbitals. Five hybrid orbitals will be used to form bonds with five fluorine atoms. There are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> sigma bonds in this compound.<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybridisation</p><p>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;sigma bonds, zero lone pair on central atom) Value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27849,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Among the given molecules&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BeF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;has zero dipole moment.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BeF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;has linear structure and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;has symmetrical trigonal planar structure and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;also has symmetrical tetrahedral structure.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;have&nbsp;non-symmetrical structure.</p><p>Hence, their net dipole moment is not zero</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27969,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{XeF}_4$","$\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}$","$\\mathrm{BF}_4^{-}$","$\\mathrm{CCl}_4$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{XeF}_4$ has square planar structure, while $\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}, \\mathrm{BF}_4^{-}$and $\\mathrm{CCl}_4$ have tetrahedral structure.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":27830,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;all have unpaired electrons so, they are paramagnetic,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>has</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>two</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>unpaired</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>electrons</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>according</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>to</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MOT</mi><mo>,</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>has</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>9</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>configuration</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>so</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>one</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>unpaired</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>electron</mi><mo>.</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>has</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>configuration</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>so</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>unpaired</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>electrons</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;Weakly attracted by magnetic field.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;does not have any unpaired electrons so they are diamagnetic,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Weakly repelled by magnetic field.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27695,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["bent, square planar","linear, square planar","bent, see-saw","linear, tetrahedral"],"answer":0,"solution":"The autoionization of bromine trifluoride is given by the reaction:<br><br>$2\\text{BrF}_3 \\rightleftharpoons \\text{BrF}_2^{\\oplus} + \\text{BrF}_4^{\\ominus}$<br><br>For the cation $\\text{BrF}_2^{\\oplus}$:<br>The central atom Br has $7$ valence electrons. Due to the positive charge, it has $7 - 1 = 6$ electrons available.<br>It forms $2$ single bonds with F atoms, leaving $4$ electrons, which constitute $2$ lone pairs.<br>Steric number = $2$ (bond pairs) + $2$ (lone pairs) = $4$.<br>The hybridization is $sp^3$. With $2$ bond pairs and $2$ lone pairs, the shape is bent (or V-shaped).<br><br>For the anion $\\text{BrF}_4^{\\ominus}$:<br>The central atom Br has $7$ valence electrons. Due to the negative charge, it has $7 + 1 = 8$ electrons available.<br>It forms $4$ single bonds with F atoms, leaving $4$ electrons, which constitute $2$ lone pairs.<br>Steric number = $4$ (bond pairs) + $2$ (lone pairs) = $6$.<br>The hybridization is $sp^3d^2$. To minimize repulsion, the $2$ lone pairs occupy opposite (trans) positions in the octahedral geometry, resulting in a square planar shape.<br><br>Thus, the shapes of the cation and anion are bent and square planar, respectively.<br><br>Answer: bent, square planar","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27960,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{H}_2>\\mathrm{B}_2>\\mathrm{Li}_2$","$\\mathrm{Li}_2>\\mathrm{H}_2>\\mathrm{B}_2$","$\\mathrm{Li}_2>\\mathrm{B}_2>\\mathrm{H}_2$","None of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"The molecular orbital configuration of the given molecules is\n$\\mathrm{H}_2=\\sigma 1 s^2$ (no electron anti-bonding)\n$\\mathrm{Li}_2=\\sigma 1 s^2 \\sigma^* 1 s^2 \\sigma 2 s^2$ (two anti-bonding electrons)\n$$\n\\mathrm{B}_2=\\sigma 1 s^2 \\sigma^* 1 s^2 \\sigma 2 s^2 \\sigma^* 2 s^2\n$$\n$$\n\\left\\{\\pi 2 p_y^1=\\pi 2 p_z^1\\right\\}\n$$\n(4 anti-bonding electrons)\nThough the bond order of all the species are same $(\\mathrm{B} . \\mathrm{O}=1)$ but stability is different. This is due to difference in the presence of no. of anti-bonding electron.\nHigher the no. of anti-bonding electron lower is the stability hence the correct order is\n$$\n\\mathrm{H}_2>\\mathrm{Li}_2>\\mathrm{B}_2\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null}]